<hr>
<p>In the book</p>

<blockquote>Paul Erd&ouml;s &amp; Ronald L. Graham: "Old and New
Problems and Results in Combinatorial Number Theory", <i>
L'Engseignement Mathematique Universite de Geneve</i>,
1980</blockquote>

<p>one can read on page 31:</p>

<blockquote>It is true that for any rational <i>a/b</i>, the
closest strict underapproximation <i>R<sub>n</sub>(a/b)</i> of <i>
a/b</i> by a sum of <i>n</i> unit fractions is given by 

<center><i>R<sub>n</sub>(a/b) = R</i><sub><i>n</i>-1</sub><i>(a/b)
+</i> 1<i>/m</i></center>

<p>where <i>m</i> is the least denominator not yet used for which
<i>R<sub>n</sub>(a/b) &lt; a/b</i>, provided that <i>n</i> is
sufficiently large.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>The authors do not give any citation of the proof of this
theorem. Does anybody know in which article it is proven or maybe
know how it can be proven?</p>

<p><i>Stefan Bartels</i></p>

