<hr>
<p>This posting is a completion to the posting of Gerry Myerson (<a
href="mailto:gerry@mpce.mq.edu.au">gerry@mpce.mq.edu.au</a>) with
two purposes:</p>

<ol>
<li>correction of my former statement concerning the proof of
Curtiss and</li>

<li>explaining my strong interest in the proof for Erd&ouml;s' and
Grahams theorem.</li>
</ol>

<p>Gerry mentioned a "former posting" saying that the proof of
Curtiss is wrong. This posting was submitted to this newsgroup by
me in July. In the meantime I found out that the proof is
definitely right (but obviously difficult to understand). (Sorry
for that.) But this mistake (of me) led to a generalization of
Curtiss' theorem that has not been published elsewhere yet: The
best underapproximation of a rational <i>a/b</i> is given by the
greedy algorithm at least for the case <i>
b</i>&nbsp;=&nbsp;-1&nbsp;mod&nbsp;<i>a</i>. (In the case <i>
a</i>=<i>b</i>=1 this is Curtiss' theorem; in the case <i>a</i>=1
this is a statement proved by Erd&ouml;s in 1950.)</p>

<p>I was also able to prove that the methods Curtiss invented work
if and only if <i>b</i>&nbsp;=&nbsp;-1&nbsp;mod&nbsp;<i>a</i>. But
there seem to be a lot more rationals for which the
underapproximation is given by the greedy algorithm. While trying
to characterize these rationals I came across the theorem of
Erd&ouml;s and Graham, which I mentioned in my first posting on
this subject.</p>

<p>Any hint on the proof of this theorem would be helpful.</p>

<p><i>Stefan Bartels</i></p>
